problem:
A circle passes through the point $(0,1),$ and is tangent to the parabola $y = x^2$ at $(2,4).$  Find the center of the circle.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

real parab (real x) {
  return(x^2);
}

draw(graph(parab,-3.5,3.5));
draw(Circle((-16/5,53/10),13*sqrt(17)/10));

dot((0,1));
dot("$(2,4)$", (2,4), E);
[/asy]

solution:
Complete the square by adding 1 to each side. Then $(x+1)^2 = 1+i=e^{\frac{i\pi}{4}} \sqrt{2}$, so $x+1 = \pm e^{\frac{i\pi}{8}}\sqrt[4]{2}$. The desired product is then
\begin{align*}
\left( -1+\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{8}\right)\sqrt[4]{2} \right) \left( -1-\cos\left( \frac{\pi}{8}\right) \sqrt[4]{2}\right) &= 1-\cos^2\left( \frac{\pi}{8}\right) \sqrt{2} \\
&= 1-\frac{\left( 1 +\cos\left( \frac{\pi}{4}\right) \right)}{2}\sqrt{2}\\
&= \boxed{\frac{1-\sqrt{2}}{2}}.
\end{align*}

problem:
An equilateral triangle $PQR$ is inscribed in the ellipse $\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1,$ so that $Q$ is at $(0,b),$ and $\overline{PR}$ is parallel to the $x$-axis, as shown below.  Also, foci $F_1$ and $F_2$ lie on sides $\overline{QR}$ and $\overline{PQ},$ respectively.  Find $\frac{PQ}{F_1 F_2}.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C;
pair[] F;
real a, b, c, s;

a = 5;
b = sqrt(3)/2*5;
c = 5/2;
s = 8;

